> Since there's been some posts about body positivity, as well as some news articles, I thought I would say this: I know it's a sensitive issue for people, and of course no one should have to feel awful about their image. But 'bodypositivity' can also lead to the trap of embracing an unhealthy life. Being very overweight has clear‚Ä¶ More risks and dangers associated with it, not to mention costs to others in the form of socialized healthcare. It's fine to be positive about yourself, but it would be foolish to use that as a reason to do nothing about your weight. Pretending that there's no problem, or implying that being overweight is just "another shape" is wrong, because that involves lying to yourself and to others. Being honest with yourself is the first step towards living a healthier life. Sources: I was reasonably overweight for a number of years.

Why is it that people say you can't be racist to white people? Whilst I agree white people do not suffer from structural racism (which I think to be the worst form of racism) which other races do, I still think you CAN be racist to white people. In fact, I think you can be racist to anyone. Google says the definition of racism is:‚Ä¶ More prejudice, discrimination, or antagonism directed against someone of a different race based on the belief that one's own race is superior. And I see no reason as to why white people cannot fit into that. Yes, obviously it isn't structural racism like I said, but there are people who joke about white people but then become sensitive when people make jokes about their own race. I just don't agree with the hypocrisy. Why can't we just all get along and stop stereotyping each other.
